{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643766","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643766"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:57:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:57:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18012"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18012"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10726"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78471"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10726"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18012"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63833"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"11226"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24965"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24968"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78471"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a lateral vertebral muscle located within the prevertebral fascia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Longus capitis","Anterior scalene","Splenius","Longus colli","Sternocleidomastoid"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior scalene\u003C/strong\u003E is a key lateral vertebral muscle contained within the prevertebral fascia. It attaches to the transverse processes of C3-C6 vertebrae superiorly and the first rib inferiorly. This muscle assists with cervical flexion and acts as an accessory muscle of respiration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options can be distinguished as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elongus capitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a prevertebral muscle that lies anterior to the vertebral column, not laterally\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elongus colli\u003C/strong\u003E is another prevertebral muscle located anteriorly, running from the atlas to T3\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esplenius\u003C/strong\u003E is a posterior neck muscle outside the prevertebral fascia that extends and rotates the head\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esternocleidomastoid\u003C/strong\u003E is a superficial neck muscle that lies outside the prevertebral fascia and functions in head rotation and flexion\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these anatomical relationships is important for procedures involving the anterior and lateral aspects of the cervical spine.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The anterior scalene muscle is a lateral vertebral muscle located within the prevertebral fascia.","Understanding the anatomy of the neck muscles is crucial for procedures involving the cervical spine and surrounding structures."],"references":["Fehrenbach, M. J., \u0026 Herring, S. W. (2015). Illustrated Anatomy of the Head and Neck-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534836/","Cramer, G. D., \u0026 Darby, S. A. (2013). Clinical anatomy of the spine, spinal cord, and ANS","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxfor